{"name":"Friend of the Rabbits","type":"item","img":"icons/creatures/mammals/rabbit-corgi-green-purple.webp","system":{"itemType":"scenarioGift","description":"You have earned the trust of the White Rabbits that carry messages throughout Wonder's impossible architecture. These magical creatures no longer fear you and will approach you willingly. You receive 2 Additional Successes when you attempt to capture or interact with a White Rabbit (reducing the Threat effectively to trivial difficulty). Once you've picked up a White Rabbit and gained its trust, your new little friends will deliver messages for you to any room in Wonder, even through seemingly closed doors, walls, or impossible distances. The rabbits can navigate Wonder's reality-bending structure instinctively, reaching locations that might be inaccessible to Hunters. You can send messages to allies separated in different Cure Rooms, communicate with Hatta Carter in the Basement, or even deliver warnings to Alice Liddell in the Hall of the Mind. The rabbits return to you after delivering their message, bringing back simple yes/no responses or brief replies (up to one sentence) from the recipient.","somaCost":0,"requirement":"Successfully capture at least one White Rabbit during your exploration of Wonder's Cure Rooms, treating it gently and earning its trust rather than harming it.","scenario":"Wonderbedlam","notes":"This Gift transforms the White Rabbits from obstacles (Threat encounters) into valuable allies. The +2 Additional Successes makes capturing them easy once you have the Gift, representing that they now approach willingly rather than fleeing. The message delivery mechanic is incredibly useful in Wonder's confusing layout: coordinate with separated party members, negotiate with Alice remotely, get hints from Hatta about upcoming areas, or warn Alicia about dangers. The rabbits can traverse Wonder's magic doors and walls because they're part of the building's living architecture. Storytellers should roleplay the rabbits as curious and playful—they might add their own observations to messages ('The lady with the lynx seemed angry') or bring back items ('The rabbit found this key'). The Gift doesn't work outside Wonder—the rabbits are bound to the bedlam. If Alice realizes Hunters have this Gift, she may try to intercept messages or send false ones. The cryptic clues about doors ('knock with hand', 'ask if anyone home') become easier to decipher with rabbit assistance."},"_id":"670c54ad4747de09"}
{"name":"Lucid Madness","type":"item","img":"icons/magic/perception/eye-tendrils-pink-purple.webp","system":{"itemType":"scenarioGift","description":"After being subjected to Wonder's reality-bending magic, you have begun to understand how madness can be made real. You are slowly figuring out how to make the weirdest ideas manifest through Wonder's impossible architecture. Once per Scene, you can spend 1 Soma to attempt to activate the mad magic of Wonder for your own purposes. State something crazy that you want to accomplish, such as 'I want to walk on walls and ceiling', 'I want my arm to stretch out of proportion to reach that ledge', 'I want to shrink down to fit through that tiny door', 'I want doors to appear where there are only walls', or 'I want time to flow backwards for a moment'. The Storyteller will ask you to make a Position Check with Opposition Level determined by the madness of your request: **OL Easy 3** for minor impossibilities (walking on walls, glowing in the dark), **OL Medium 5** for moderate madness (stretching limbs, changing size), **OL Hard 7** for major reality warping (creating doors, manipulating time, phasing through walls). If you succeed, you gain a temporary Descriptor representing your declared impossibility for the rest of the Scene. If you fail, you have spent your Soma in vain and nothing happens. The effect immediately ends if someone makes it clear that what you are doing is utter madness—doubt and disbelief shatter the effect.","somaCost":1,"requirement":"Experience Wonder's Gift 'Place of Pure Madness' at least once—be teleported randomly and suffer a side effect (Shrunk, Enlarged, or Confused) after attempting to alter Wonder's structure.","scenario":"Wonderbedlam","notes":"This is one of the most creative and open-ended Gifts in Broken Tales. It allows Hunters to temporarily wield Wonder's reality-bending power for themselves. The 1 Soma cost per attempt encourages strategic use. The scaling OL (3/5/7 based on madness level) lets Storytellers balance power—asking to glow = easy, asking to fly = hard. The temporary Descriptor lasts entire Scene, making successful uses very powerful. The 'shattering through disbelief' mechanic is crucial: if NPCs or allies point out the impossibility ('You can't walk on the ceiling, that's insane!'), the effect ends. This encourages Hunters to act confidently and not draw attention to the madness. Clever Hunters will use this to: access unreachable areas (stretch arms, shrink size), bypass obstacles (phase through doors, walk on ceilings), surprise enemies (invisible, extra limbs), or even manipulate Wonder itself (create doors, freeze time briefly). The Storyteller should encourage creative uses but apply the OL fairly—minor utility = Easy, combat advantages = Medium, reality warping = Hard. This Gift stops working outside Wonder—it's tied to the bedlam's magic. It represents the Hunter beginning to internalize Alice's philosophy: reality is what perception makes it."},"_id":"89e2e6a64b49cbd4"}
{"name":"The Forgotten Queen","type":"item","img":"icons/equipment/head/crown-thorns-gold-purple.webp","system":{"itemType":"scenarioGift","description":"**SPECIAL GIFT FOR REGINA THE THIEF OF HEARTS ONLY.** Confusing flashbacks and painful emotions grip your mind as you explore Wonder. You've been here before as a patient, but the memories are fragmented and unclear. Something terrible happened to you in this place, something Alice Liddell tried to erase. Are you sure you want to remember? Once per Scene, you can attempt to remember something from your forgotten time in Wonder. Choose a specific place (Rabbit Hole, Labyrinth of Doors, Caterpillars' Greenhouse, Basement, Hall of the Mind) or a specific subject (Alice, Hatta, Cheshire, a Patient, the White Rabbits, Wonder itself). The Storyteller will give you one piece of useful information about that place or subject: a hidden Descriptor, a secret Gift they possess, their true Agenda, a weakness, or a crucial detail about how they function. This insider knowledge can be invaluable for navigating Wonder and confronting Alice. However, remembering is intensely painful—these are memories Alice tried to destroy for a reason. For the rest of the Scene after remembering, whenever you use one of your own Gifts, roll 1 die. On a result of 5 or 6, you lose 1 Soma as the mental strain overwhelms you, and you are no longer so sure that you are the Queen. Your identity begins to fragment and blur, just as Alice intended.","somaCost":0,"requirement":"Enter and explore any of Wonder's Cure Rooms as Regina the Thief of Hearts, triggering suppressed memories of your previous time as a patient in this bedlam.","scenario":"Wonderbedlam","notes":"This Regina-exclusive Gift adds a deeply personal horror element to Wonderbedlam. It reveals that Regina has history with Wonder—she was a patient here, possibly when she was struggling with her own identity and crimes. Alice tried to erase Regina's memories and remake her, but Regina escaped (or was released as 'cured') with her identity intact but fragmented. The once per Scene information gathering is powerful—Regina can learn NPCs' hidden Gifts, secret Agendas, or vulnerabilities by 'remembering' previous encounters. The dice roll penalty (5-6 = lose 1 Soma when using own Gifts) creates tension: use your powers and risk losing yourself, or hold back and survive on mundane actions? The 'no longer sure you are the Queen' effect is narrative—Storytellers can describe Regina questioning her memories, personality, or even her role as a Hunter. Was Regina of Hearts a fake identity Alice gave her? Is the Hunter Regina or someone Alice created? This Gift transforms Wonderbedlam from a rescue mission into Regina's personal nightmare of confronting her own past. Storytellers should drop hints: Patients who recognize Regina, Alice commenting 'I remember you', or Hatta mentioning 'that Queen patient from years ago'. The Gift doesn't cost Soma to activate but the penalty costs Soma over time—reflecting that remembering is slowly destroying Regina's sense of self. This can lead to powerful roleplay: Does Regina want to remember who she was before Alice's treatment? Or is forgetting a mercy?"},"_id":"d34108fce4acb80f"}